        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> caused by slash normalization. I fixed the c code, should've realized this path calls `uv.spawn` directly as well. :(\n> \n> [neovim/runtime/lua/vim/_core/system.lua](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/6a87ef75b3f141e175399e87c5518ec11102877d/runtime/lua/vim/_core/system.lua#L320-L326)\n> \n> Lines 320 to 326 in [6a87ef7](/neovim/neovim/commit/6a87ef75b3f141e175399e87c5518ec11102877d)\n> \n>    local cmd1 = vim.fn.exepath(cmd) \n>    if cmd1 ~= '' then \n>      cmd = cmd1 \n>    end \n>  end \n>   \n>  local handle, pid_or_err = uv.spawn(cmd, opts, on_exit) \n> \n> `exepath` returns `c:/windows/system32/cmd.exe`\n> [@rsinghgit](https://github.com/rsinghgit), as a temp workaround, could you please try to change `cmd = cmd1` to `cmd = cmd1:gsub(\"/\", \"\\\\\")`, then start with `nvim --luamod-dev`\n\nThat worked for me. Note that cmd = cmd1 is on line 314 in v0.13.0+375 build. Thanks!\n\nAs a side note - overriding vim.ui.open to use rundll32 in init.lua also worked for me:\n```\nif vim.fn.has('win32') == 1 then\n  -- @todo - remove this when vim.ui.open is fixed upstream.\n  vim.ui.open = function(uri)\n    return vim.system(\n      { 'rundll32', 'url.dll,FileProtocolHandler', uri },\n      { detach = true }\n    )\n  end\n  vim.g.netrw_browsex_viewer = 'rundll32 url.dll,FileProtocolHandler'\nend\n```\n",
